<section xml:id="sec-factoring-and-roots-of-polynomial-functions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Factoring and Roots of Polynomial Functions</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Recall that our goal is to be able to factor polynomials, in a similar way that we can factor quadratic functions. The question is: how do we find factors?
    </p>
    
    <example>
      <p>
        Recall that quadratics can be written in factored form. For example,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>f(x) \amp = x^2-x-6</mrow>
        <mrow>f(x) \amp = (x+2)(x-3)</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              The factors are <m>x+2</m> and <m>x-3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The zeros are <m>x = -2</m> and <m>x = 3</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that each zero corresponds to a factor. In other words,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\text{Zero of the polynomial} \iff \text{Factor of the polynomial}</mrow>
      </md>
    </example>
    
    <p>
      This relationship extends to any polynomial function, and is called the <em>factor theorem</em>.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  
  
  
  <subsection>
    <title>Factor Theorem</title>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>Factor theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x)</m> be a polynomial. Then, <m>x - a</m> is a factor of the polynomial <m>f(x)</m> if and only if <m>f(a) = 0</m>. In other words,
          <ol type="a">
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f(a) = 0</m>, then <m>x - a</m> is a factor of <m>f</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>x - a</m> is a factor of <m>f</m>, then <m>f(a) = 0</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      This provides an equivalence between <m>x - a</m> being a factor of <m>f(x)</m>, and <m>a</m> being a root of <m>f(x)</m>. We also know that <m>x-a</m> being a factor of <m>f(x)</m> means that dividing <m>f(x)</m> by <m>x-a</m> gives a remainder of 0. Putting it together, these are all equivalent:
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow>\begin{pmatrix} f(x) \\ \text{has factor} \\ x - a \end{pmatrix} \iff \begin{pmatrix} f(x) \text{ has root $a$} \\ \text{or, } f(a) = 0 \end{pmatrix} \iff \begin{pmatrix} \text{$f(x)$ divided by $x - a$} \\ \text{gives remainder 0} \end{pmatrix}</mrow>
    </md>
    
    <example>
      <p>
        For the polynomial function <m>f(x) = 2x^3 - 3x^2 - 10x + 3</m>, to determine if <m>x-3</m> is a factor, evaluate <m>f(3)</m>,
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>f(3) \amp = 2(3)^3 - 3(3)^2 - 10(3) + 3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = 0</mrow>
      </md>
      <p>
        This means that <m>x=3</m> is a root, so by the factor theorem, <m>x - 3</m> is a factor of <m>f</m>.
      </p>
    </example>
    
    <exercises>
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For each zero of a polynomial function <m>f(x)</m>, give the corresponding factor.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>f(1)=0</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>f(-3)=0</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>f(4)=0</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>f(a)=0</m></p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>f(x) = x^3 - x^2 - 5x + 2</m>, determine if each binomial is a factor.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>x-1</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>x+2</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>f(x) = x^4 + 6x^3 + 4x^2 + 7x + 60</m>, determine if each binomial is a factor.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>x+5</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>x-2</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>k</m> so that <m>x+1</m> is a factor of <m>2x^4 + (k+1)x^2 - 6kx + 11</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What are all values of <m>k</m> for which <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> is a zero of 
            <m>P(x) = -4x^3 + 2x^2 - 2kx + k^3</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>x-a</m> is a factor of <m>2x^3 - a x^2 + (1-a^2)x + 5</m>, what is <m>a</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find values for <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>x-1</m> is a factor of both 
            <m>x^3 + x^2 + ax + b</m> and <m>x^3 - x^2 - ax + b</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
  </subsection>
  
  <subsection>
    <title>The Remainder Theorem</title>
    <p>
      The remainder theorem states that when a polynomial <m>f(x)</m> is divided by a binomial <m>x - a</m>, the remainder is <m>f(a)</m>.
    </p>
    
    <theorem>
      <title>Remainder theorem</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If a polynomial <m>f(x)</m> is divided by a binomial <m>x - a</m>, the remainder is equal to the function evaluated at <m>a</m>, i.e. <m>f(a)</m>.
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\boxed{f(a) = \begin{matrix} \text{remainder of } p(x) \\ \text{divided by } x-a \end{matrix}}</mrow>
        </md>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    
    <p>
      In other words, to find the remainder after division by <m>x-a</m>, you can just evaluate the polynomial at <m>x = a</m>, instead of going through the division process.
    </p>
    
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-remainder-theorem">
      <title>Exercises</title>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the remainder for each polynomial division, using the remainder theorem.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>(x^2 + 5x + 4) \div (x-2)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 + 3x^2 - 5x + 2) \div (x+1)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^2 - 2x) \div (x-4)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 - 2x^2 - 3) \div (x+2)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(2x - 4x^3 - 3x^2) \div (x-2)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>\dfrac{x^3 + 2x^2 - 3x + 9}{x+3}</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 + 2x^2 - 3x + 5) \div (x-3)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>\dfrac{x^4 - 3x^2 - 5x + 2}{x-2}</m></p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find each value of <m>m</m> from the given division and remainder.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>(mx^2 - 2x - 1) \div (x-1)</m>, remainder <m>-2</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 - mx^2 + 17x + 6) \div (x-3)</m>, remainder <m>12</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^4 - 2x^3 - x^2 + mx + 2) \div (2x-1)</m>, remainder <m>-1</m></p></li>
            <li><p><m>(2x^4 - x^3 - 4x^2 + x - m) \div (x+3)</m>, remainder <m>3</m></p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>k</m> for each polynomial, using the given remainder condition.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p>When <m>f(x) = 4x^3 + kx^2 - 7x + 9</m> is divided by <m>x+3</m>, the remainder is <m>-33</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 + 4x^2 - x + k) \div (x-1)</m> has remainder <m>3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 + x^2 + kx - 15) \div (x-2)</m> has remainder <m>3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>(x^3 + kx^2 + x + 5) \div (x+2)</m> has remainder <m>3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>(kx^3 + 3x + 1) \div (x+2)</m> has remainder <m>3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>(3x^2 + 6x - 10) \div (x+k)</m> has remainder <m>14</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>x^3 + kx + 1</m> is divided by <m>x-2</m>, the remainder is <m>-3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>x^3 - x^2 + kx - 8</m> is divided by <m>x-4</m>, the remainder is <m>0</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>2x^4 + kx^2 - 3x + 5</m> is divided by <m>x-2</m>, the remainder is <m>3</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>x^3 + kx + 6</m> is divided by <m>x+2</m>, the remainder is <m>4</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>p(x)=kx^{50} + 2x^{30} + 4x + 7</m> is divided by <m>x+1</m>, the remainder is <m>23</m>. Find <m>k</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The polynomial <m>p(x)= -2x^3 + cx^2 - 5x + 2</m> has the same remainder when divided by <m>x-2</m> and by <m>x+1</m>. Find <m>c</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the unknown coefficients.
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li><p><m>3x^3 - mx^2 + nx + 2</m> has remainders <m>-6</m> upon division by <m>x+1</m> and <m>18</m> upon division by <m>x-2</m>. Find <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>2x^3 + mx^2 + nx - 14</m> has remainders <m>22</m> upon division by <m>x-2</m> and <m>-53</m> upon division by <m>x+3</m>. Find <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>mx^3 - 3x^2 + nx + 2</m> has remainders <m>-1</m> upon division by <m>x+3</m> and <m>-4</m> upon division by <m>x-2</m>. Find <m>m</m> and <m>n</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>3x^3 + ax^2 + bx - 9</m> has remainders <m>-5</m> upon division by <m>x-2</m> and <m>-16</m> upon division by <m>x+1</m>. Find <m>a,b</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p>When <m>kx^3 + mx^2 + x - 2</m> is divided by <m>x-1</m>, the remainder is <m>6</m>. When this polynomial is divided by <m>x+2</m>, the remainder is <m>12</m>. Find <m>k</m> and <m>m</m>.</p></li>
            <li><p><m>x^4 + kx^3 - mx + 15</m> has no remainder when divided by <m>x-1</m> and <m>x+3</m>. Find <m>k</m> and <m>m</m>.</p></li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When <m>p(x)=3x^4 + kx^2 + 7</m> is divided by <m>x-1</m>, the remainder is the same as when <m>f(x)=x^4 + kx - 4</m> is divided by <m>x-2</m>. Find <m>k</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When <m>x^3 + kx^2 - 2x - 7</m> is divided by <m>x+1</m>, the remainder is <m>5</m>. What is the remainder when it is divided by <m>x-1</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For <m>p(x)=x^3 - r x^2 + 3x + r^2</m>, find all values of <m>r</m> so that <m>p(3)=18</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When <m>x^n + x - 8</m> is divided by <m>x-2</m>, the remainder is <m>10</m>. Find <m>n</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      
      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            When <m>x^2 + 5x - 2</m> is divided by <m>x+a</m>, the remainder is <m>8</m>. Find all possible values of <m>a</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercises>
    
    
  </subsection>
  
